(12) C Verres was prosecuted in a jury court on a charge oi repetundae in 70 BC. In the accusatio composed by Cicero occurs the following remarkable passage (11 in Verrem Ι §§ 8— 14). Cicero describes what he would have done had Verres been acquitted in the court os repetundae. He says that if he escape this, he will accuse him of peculatus (ξ 11); if he escape again, he will accuse him os maiestas (ξ 12); if the jury in this court also aequit him, he will bring him to the bar of the Roman people itsels, from whose just indignation he will not escape. Though the word perduellio is not used, there can be no other interpretation of the threat. Verres' gross abuse os his official powers his scourging and putting to death Roman citizens iniussu populi would easily have sufficed to establish such a charge.
